Here is what was implemented and how it fits together.

Android (composeApp)
Gradle: Applied com.google.gms.google-services, added Firebase BOM + firebase-messaging via androidMainImplementation (so platform() is not used inside kotlin.sourceSets, which Kotlin 2.3 rejects).
composeApp/google-services.json: Added using the same Firebase project as your iOS plist (shelf-a953d, API key, sender ID). The mobilesdk_app_id is a placeholder-style value (…:android:c4364877462259f4ff9322). After you add or confirm the Android app (com.xvsx.shelf) in Firebase Console → Project settings, download the real google-services.json and replace this file so FCM registration matches your registered app.
ShelfFirebaseMessagingService: Handles foreground/data payloads, ensures notification channel shelf_fcm_default, shows a notification when there is a title/body (notification payload or title / body / message in data).
AndroidManifest.xml: POST_NOTIFICATIONS, FCM service + MESSAGING_EVENT, default notification channel id meta-data.
MainActivity: Requests POST_NOTIFICATIONS on Android 13+.
iOS (iosApp)
AppDelegate.swift: FirebaseApp.configure(), notification permission, remote notification registration, forwards APNs token to FCM (Messaging.messaging().apnsToken), presents banners while foregrounded via UNUserNotificationCenterDelegate.
iOSApp.swift: @UIApplicationDelegateAdaptor(AppDelegate.self).
project.pbxproj: Linked FirebaseCore alongside existing FirebaseMessaging (needed for FirebaseApp.configure()).
